# From Djot

@summary
Djot fixes many Markdown ambiguities with a fuller light-markup syntax. Lessmark takes a stricter route: fewer spellings, named blocks, and no raw content containers.

## What changes

Djot is close to Markdown but more coherent. Lessmark is less flexible on purpose. It turns structure into named blocks instead of general containers and attributes on any element.

## Headings and prose

Both formats keep plain prose readable. Djot heading markers use one or more {{code:#}} characters. Lessmark uses the same heading shape and canonical blank-line formatting.

@code lang="djot"
# Release notes

Plain prose with _emphasis_ and *strong text*.

@code lang="lessmark"
# Release notes

Plain prose with {{em:emphasis}} and {{strong:strong text}}.

## Divs and containers

Djot has generic containers. Lessmark uses named blocks with fixed attributes.

@code lang="djot"
::: warning
Do not publish unreviewed examples.
:::

@code lang="lessmark"
  @callout kind="warning"
  Do not publish unreviewed examples.

## Attributes

Djot can attach attributes broadly. Lessmark only accepts attributes declared for the block.

@code lang="djot"
[Install guide]{#install .primary}

@code lang="lessmark"
{{link:Install guide|docs/getting-started}}

## Tables, footnotes, math, and diagrams

Use Lessmark's typed blocks for structures that Djot writes as built-in light markup.

@code lang="lessmark"
  @table columns="Feature|Status"
  Footnotes|supported
  Math|supported

  @math notation="tex"
  E = mc^2

## When to keep Djot

Keep Djot when you want a broad Markdown-like language with attributes and containers. Use Lessmark when the goal is a smaller grammar, stable AST shape, and source that rejects unknown structure.

